@node "Dist" "Distrubition"

    @{b}Distrubition@{ub}

        In this version of Aavd you will get the following files:


            Aavd            - This is the program itself.
            Aavd.info       - An icon.
            Aavd.guide      - This doc.
            Aavd.guide.info - Documentation icon.
            Install         - An installation script.
            Install.info    - An icon that executes installer.
            fonts/aavd.font - A nice(??) small font.
            fonts/aavd/6    - This font data.

        You one or more of these files are missing, then (obvously)
        your archive isn't complete. If you want a complete archive,
        then mail me a letter (preferably e-mail) and I'll send you the
        latest release. @{"Click here" link "disc" 0} to get my address.
@endnode

@node "install" "How to install AAVD"

    @{b}Installation@{ub}

        Installing Aavd is about as simple as it can get. Double
        click on the "Install" icon and Aavd will install itself.

        For all of you that rather installes by hand, all you've got
        to to is copy "Aavd" and "Aavd.guide" to some logic place
        and the contents of "fonts" to, for example, "fonts:".
@endnode

@node "what" "What is AAVD anyway?"

    @{b}Description@{ub}

        Have you ever used the @{i}OLVWM@{ui} window manager for x-windows
        (used mostly under SUN OS/Solaris and LINUX).

        Then you've noticed the @{i}Virtual Desktop@{ui} window, and know
        what it is used for. If you don't, just run this program
        and you will soon find out what it does.

        AAVD will open a window that shows a miniature of the
        default public screen (usually the Workbench) where each "box"
        represents a window. From the AAVD window you are able to:
            o @{b}move a window@{ub}
            o @{b}resize a window@{ub}
            o @{b}activate a window@{ub}
            o @{b}depth arrange a window@{ub}
            o @{b}center the screen over a window@{ub}
            o @{b}center the screen over a part of the screen@{ub}
            o @{b}and some more...@{ub}

        I have tried to use the common mouse techiques in AAVD, this
        means that if you want to activate a window, click on the
        left mouse button, to drag, just drag as you use to do. You
        can even cancel the operation with the right button. See
        below for a list of what you can do, and how to do it.


        o @{b}How to activate a window:@{ub}
            Click the left button.

        o @{b}How to move a window:@{ub}
            Press the left button, move the window to it's new
            position and release the button. This operation is canceld
            if the right button is pressed before the left is released.

        o @{b}How to depth arrange a window:@{ub}
            Click on the right button.
            The window will be move to the front, unless it's already
            at the front, in which case it will be moved to the back.
            This is not as smooth as clicking on the depth gadget on
            the window, since I've not figured out how to determine
            if a window is covered by another window.

        o @{b}How to resize a window:@{ub}
            Press the right button, move the mouse and release the
            button when you're done. The left button can be used to
            cancel this operation.

        o @{b}How to center the screen over a window:@{ub}
            Double click with the left button on the window.

        o @{b}How to center the screen over a part of the screen@{ub}
            Double click the left button on the part of the screen
            you want to center. Make sure you dont click on a window.

        o @{b}How to use the menus@{ub}
            Since AAVD uses the right mousebutton to depth arrange
            windows there are one minor probem when you also wants to
            use @{"menus" link "menus" 0}. Both needs the right button to be pressed.

            Therefore, when you wants to use the menus, you MUST
            place the pointer ON the windowborder or OUTSIDE the
            window.

        That's about it. Not very hard to learn, was it...
@endnode

@node "menus" "Using the Menus"

    @{b}Menus@{ub}
        In order to be able to view the menus you @{b}MUST@{ub} press the
        menubutton @{b}OUTSIDE@{ub}, or @{b}ON@{ub} @{b}the borders@{ub} of the AAVD window.
        That's because AAVD normally uses the right mouse button
        to resize/depth arrange windows.

        +----------------+-----------------------+
        | Project        | Special               |
        +----------------+-----------------------+
        | Use Current   U| Reject This Screen  R |
        | Save Current  S+-----------------------+
        | Prefs         P|
        | About          |
        |================|
        | Quit          Q|
        +----------------+

        @{b}The Project Menu@{ub}

            @{b}o Use Current@{ub}  (Left Amiga-U)
                This has the same effect as if you would press USE from
                the @{"configuration window" link "gui" 0}. The reason for this to be in
                the menu is that there should be a simple and fast way to
                use new snapshots. (That is, save them to ENV:).

            @{b}o Save Current@{ub} (Left Amiga-S)
                Saves the current settings.

            @{b}o Prefs@{ub} (Left Amiga-P)
                Opens the configuration window.

            @{b}o About@{ub}
                About AAVD.

            @{b}o Quit@{ub} (Left Amiga-Q)
                Well, I guess it speaks for itself...



        @{b}The Special Menu@{ub}

            @{b}o Reject This Screen@{ub} (Left Amiga-R)
                Selecting this menu adds the active screen to the list of
                screens Aavd shouldn't be allowed to open on. The main
                reason for this menu is that some pubscreens (for example
                DirOpus) can't be closed while Aavd is visiting the
                screen. Instead of manually specify that Aavd shouldn't
                be allowed to use this screen, simply select this menu
                and close the screen (program).
@endnode

@node "use" "How to use AAVD"


    @{b}How to use AAVD@{ub}

        AAVD can be started both from shell and from workbench. Items
        marked with a 'W' can be use as a tool type and items marked
        with a 'S' can be used from shell.


   @{b}Keywords:@{ub}
    The following options requires some extra info, for example XPOS=100.

   W S  @{b}PUBSCREEN@{ub}           Name of the pubscreen to open AAVD on,
                            default is the default public screen
                            (usually Workbench).
   W S  @{b}XPOS@{ub}                X position top open the AAVD window on.
                            -1 means the first visible xpos.
   W S  @{b}YPOS@{ub}                Y position. -1 means the first visible ypos.
   W S  @{b}WIDTH@{ub}               The width of the AAVD window.
   W S  @{b}HEIGHT@{ub}              The height.
   W S  @{b}FONTNAME@{ub}            Used to specify what font to use when
                            printing the windowtitles. Defaults to
                            aavd.font.
   W S  @{b}FONTSIZE@{ub}            Use this to specify what font size to use.
                            Default is 6.
   W S  @{b}SECS@{ub}                Number of seconds between timedepending
                            events.
   W S  @{b}MICS@{ub}                Number of microseconds between timedepending
                            events.
   W S  @{b}ACTIVATEKEY@{ub}         Hotkey used to activate AAVD. Default is
                            <Shift Lcommand Space>.

   W    @{b}SNAP#x@{ub}              What hotkey used to snapshot a screen
                            position. x may be 1 to 4. Default is
                            <rawkey Shift F1> to <rawkey Shift F4>.
   W    @{b}RECALL#x@{ub}            What hotkey used to recall a snapshotted
                            screen position. x may be 1 to 4. Default
                            is <rawkey F1> to <rawkey F4>.

   @{b}Switches@{ub}
    These options is activated just by entering their names, for example
    'aavd NOTEXT' to activate NOTEXT.

   W S  @{b}NOSCREENDRAW@{ub}        When you drag or resize a window, then
                            no box will appear around the real window,
                            but only in the AAVD window.
   W S  @{b}NOBACKDROP@{ub}          Ignore all backdrop window. Usually the
                            Workbench window is backdrop.
   W S  @{b}NOAAVDWIN@{ub}           Ignore the AAVD window in the AAVD Window(?).
   W S  @{b}NOTITLEBAR@{ub}          This will open AAVD without titlebar,
                            close-, zoom-, and depthgadgets. Used
                            together with LOCKSIZE this will result
                            in a window with minimal borders.
   W S  @{b}JUMPSCROLL@{ub}          When this switch is used, then AAVD will
                            force the screen to scroll "whole"
                            screen parts instead of single pixels
                            when the user scrolls the screen. For
                            example, if you got a screen that is
                            twice as wide as the visible part,
                            then you will in the beginning see
                            the left part of the screen. If you
                            now scrolls the screen some pixels to
                            the right, AAVD will move the entire
                            screen so that you'll see the whole
                            right part of the screen.
   W S  @{b}NOTEXT@{ub}              Don't print the window titles in the boxes.
   W S  @{b}SAFE@{ub}                This means that you cannot move a window who
                            got no dragbar, resize a window without a
                            sizegadget, deapth arrange a window
                            without a depth gadget or make a window
                            smaller/larger then it's minimun/maximun
                            size.
   W S  @{b}LOCKPOS@{ub}             This locks the position of the AAVD window.
                            With other words, you can't move it.
   W S  @{b}LOCKSIZE@{ub}            Opens AAVD without a resizing gadget.
   W S  @{b}FOLLOW@{ub}              This tells the AAVD window to follow the
                            visible screen when you scroll it.
   W S  @{b}DEVIDE@{ub}              This option devides the AAVD window into a
                            number of smaller windows. Each of those
                            windows represenent a piece of the screen
                            that is the same size as the visible part of
                            the screen. If you didn't get it, just try
                            it...
   W S  @{b}NOSCREENBOX@{ub}         Don't draw the box that tells you where the
                            visible part of the screen is.
   W S  @{b}SCREENBOXINFRONT@{ub}    Draw the screenbox in front of the window
                            boxes, instead of below.


   @{b}Commoditie standards@{ub}

   W S  @{b}CX_PRIORITY@{ub}         Sets the priority of the commoditiy. Default
                            is 0.
   W S  @{b}CX_POPUP@{ub}            Use this if you want to open the
                            configuration window when AAVD is started.
   W S  @{b}CX_POPKEY@{ub}           This specifies what hotkey that should be
                            used to open the configuration window.
                            Default is <ctrl f1>.


    (W) Can be used from Workbench.
    (S) Can be used from shell.

    @{b}Hot Keys@{ub}

        These are the default hotkeys used by AAVD.

            @{b}Ctrl-F1@{ub} : Show the AAVD configuration window

            @{b}Shift-F1@{ub} to
            @{b}Shift-F4@{ub} : Snapshow screen position 1 to 4.

            @{b}F1@{ub} to @{b}F4@{ub} : Recall screen position 1 to 4.

            @{b}Shift-Left Amiga-Space@{ub} : Activate and center AAVD window.

    @{b}Examples@{ub}

        o The simplest way to start AAVD...

            > aavd

        o To open AAVD on a specific position with a specific size...

            > aavd XPOS = 50 YPOS = 30 WIDTH = 150 HEIGHT = 75

            Open AAVD on position (50,30) width the width 150 and
            the height 75.

        o To open AAVD on the first Directory Opus screen...

            > aavd PUBSCREEN = DOPUS.1

            DOPUS.1 is the name of the first DirOpus screen.

        o To open AAVD in the topleft corner of the visible part of
          the screen, making it impossible to move the window around
          and make it follow the screen when it is scrolled...

            > aavd XPOS = -1 YPOS = -1 LOCKPOS FOLLOW

    @{b}NOTE@{ub}

        All of the above switched can be changed from the configuration
        window. You open that window by pressing <CTRL-F1> or selecting
        the <Show Interface> button from the 'Exchange' tool.
@endnode

@node "keyboard" "Using the Keyboard"

    @{b}Keyboard@{ub}

        The are some windowmanipulating operations that may be done
        from the keyboard.

        Make sure that the AAVD window is active, then place the pointer
        over the window you wish too manipulate and press one of the
        following keys:


        @{b}z@{ub} or @{b}Z@{ub}      : Zooms a window. Has the same effect as if you would
                      have pressed the Zoom gadget on the window.

        @{b}k@{ub} or @{b}K@{ub}      : Closes (kills) a window. The window under the
                      pointer will be closed.

        @{b}M@{ub}           : Maximize the window.

        @{b}m@{ub}           : Minimize the window.

        @{b}Cursor keys@{ub} : Jumps to next "virtual" screen. This will work best
                      if the screen is of a multiple size of the visible
                      area, i.e. a normal PAL screen should have the size
                      (x*640)*(y*256) where x and y are integers.
                      For example, a PAL screen with the size 1920*512
                      (3*640)*(2*256) will have 6 (3*2) "virtual"
                      screens.

        @{b}Shift Up@{ub}    : Changes to the next allowed screen.

        @{b}Shift Down@{ub}  : Changes to the previous allowed screen.
@endnode

@node "gui" "Configuration Window"

    @{b}Configuration Window@{ub}

        The configuration is devided up into a number of pages.
        On top of each page you will find a number of buttons
        used to switch to other pages, and on the bottom is
        the buttons Save, Use and Cancel.



        @{b}o Page 1@{ub}
            On this page you will find the snapshot/recall hotkeys.

        @{b}o Page 2@{ub}
            Here you will find all configuration switches.

        @{b}o Page 3@{ub}
            This is the page where you enter which screens AAVD is
            allowed/not allowed be in. For AAVD to be able to open
            on a screen, the screen name must be specified in the
            @{b}Allowed@{ub} list and may not be in the @{b}Rejected@{ub} list.
            Ordinary wildcards, such as #, ?, *, [], is supported.

        @{b}o Page 4@{ub}
            Here is some various stuff, such as activation/popup
            hotkeys, starting size of the AAVD window, time intervall
            between time dependent events. Node the @{b}Grab@{ub} button that
            grabs the current AAVD windows size and position and puts
            it in the size/position gadgets.

        @{b}o Page 5@{ub}
            On this page you may specify what colors AAVD sould use.



        From V1.5 there is also menus attached to this window. They look,
        and work, like ordinary prefsmenus.

        The configuation window is designed to fit into a lowresolution
        NTSC screen and uses the Topaz 8 font. The reason for this is
        that writing font- and screensizeindependent GUI's take too much
        time and is extreamly boring (trust me). To all of you running a
        megasuperhires-twice interlaced screenmode, all I can say is
        sorry..
        In any case, you don't really have to use the config window
        THAT much...

        I will problaby write a MUI version of AAVD later on.
@endnode

@node "tech" "Technical info about AAVD"

    @{b}Technical info.@{ub}

        AAVD patches some of the rom routines to find out when a window
        is moved, resized, depth arranenged, opened, closed and so on.
        The patch is very simple, first it calls the original routine
        and then it will signal the AAVD task so that the AAVD window
        may be updated.

        Here's a list of the routines that will be patched:

            from intuition.library:

                @{b}OpenWindow()@{ub}
                @{b}OpenWindowTagList()@{ub}
                @{b}CloseWindow()@{ub}

            from layers.library

                @{b}MoveSizeLayer()@{ub}
                @{b}BehindLayer()@{ub}
                @{b}UpfrontLayer()@{ub}


        Because of these patches, it may be possible that AAVD doesn't
        work to well with other programs that patches these routines.

        You can only run one AAVD at a time. This because of the
        patches. If you, for example, should start two AAVD's at the same
        time (A and B), then AAVD A will get pointers to the original
        routines, and AAVD B will get the pointers to AAVD A's routines.
        It will problaby work without problems so far. The problem is
        that if you should quit AAVD A before AAVD B the following will
        happen:

            when AAVD A quits, it will restore the original routine
            pointers. This means that AAVD B will no longer receive
            signals when windows are moved, opened, resized and so on.

            And when you then quits AAVD B, it will restore the pointers
            to how it looked when it was started (to AAVD A's routines).
            AAVD A's routines will now be deallocated by the system, and
            the next time the system calls one of these patched routines
            you will get a GURU!!!

    @{b}Warnings@{ub}

        Since AAVD make these pacthes, there are some things that you
        ought to know. For example, what may happen if another program
        patches one of these functions too?

        If that's the case, here what to do...

        1) Don't use AAVD and that other program at the same time, that's
           the simplest way to avoid trouble (read crashes).

        2) Start both the programs, and keep them running. This should
           work just fine too. There are only trouble if you try to quit
           AAVD or that other program.

        3) If you want to quit AAVD or the other program, make sure you
           start it last. In this case, everything should be alright.

        4) If you got to this point, my advise to you is this. ALWAYS
           start AAVD first. If you want to close AAVD, AAVD first checks
           too see if the functions has been repatched. In this case,
           AAVD will display a requester with a warning. You may now
           either take you chance and quit directly, or make a delayed
           quit. With a delaied quit means that AAVD checks the patches
           every second, and as soon as all function saftly may be
           repatched AAVD will quit. The disadvantage is that it's
           possible that the patches never will be restored, in which
           case AAVD will wait forever and never quit (you are left with
           an unuseable window). A direct quit, however, will problaby
           crash the machine when the patches has been restored, since
           this will result (sooner or later) in a call to unused memory.


    @{b}Timer based events.@{ub}

        Some events cannot be monitored by patches, since the system
        doesn't call a function. This events must thererfore be checked
        now and then. These are the events that are checked every 125000
        microsecond (by default).

            o If the user has @{b}activated another screen@{ub}, then if that
              screen is either public or the workbench AAVD will
              move the window to that screen. From V1.4 of AAVD
              you may specify exactly what screens AAVD should
              be allowed to open on. See @{"GUI" link "gui" 0} for more info.

            o If the @{b}screen has been scrolled@{ub}, then AAVD will redraw the
              window. If the @{"FOLLOW" link "use" 48} template is used, then AAVD will also
              move the window.

            o If the user has @{b}activated another window@{ub}, then redraw the
              AAVD window.

        The time of 125000 microseconds can be changed with the @{"SECS" link "use" 32} and
        @{"MICS" link "use" 34} keywords.


    @{b}Screen Layer Locking@{ub}

        Whenever a window is moved or resized (from the AAVD window),
        AAVD will lock all the layers on the screen with
        @{b}LockLayers(screen->LayerInfo)@{ub}.

        This means that all output will be frozen on that screen when you
        move a window, exactly as it will do if you, for example, moves a
        window the "real" way.

        This is done to prevent trash to be left on the screen after AAVD
        has drawn the border over the real window.

        So, if there should be any problems where AAVD suddenly frezes
        the system (pointer stuck, no guru and so on) the problem surley
        has something to do with this locking, (the layers where for some
        reason not unlocked). If this should happen, PLEASE, send me a
        letter where you describe how you managed to do this.


    @{b}Closing a window@{ub}

        By pressing '@{"k" link "keyboard" 0}' on the keyboard you may close a window from AAVD.
        AAVD sets up a temporary messageport and create a fake
        @{b}IDCMP_CLOSEWINDOW@{ub} message that is sent to the windows UserPort.
        This will work without problem for the very most of the windows,
        but NOT for CON: windows, for some reason. This means that you
        cannot close, for example, a shell window from AAVD.

    @{b}Jump scroll switch@{ub}

        When this switch is used, AAVD checks for small screen movments
        to detect if the screen should be scrolled. Unforntally this only
        works for autoscroll screens. Therefore AAVD forces the screen to
        autoscroll by setting the @{b}AUTOSCROLL@{ub} bit in the @{b}screen->Flags@{ub}
        field. If this is ok to do, or not, can be discussed. It does
        seem to work without any problems (at least it has for me), but
        IF you should encounter any problems, dont use @{"JUMPSCROLL" link "use" 0} and
        AAVD will never touch screen->Flags. If you still want to use
        @{"JUMPSCROLL" link "use" 0}, drop @{"me" link "disc" 0} a letter and I'll send you a copy if AAVD
        where this behavior is disabled...
@endnode

@node "bugs" "Nobody is perfect"

    @{b}Known bugs@{ub}

        There is no keyboard shortcuts to the listview gadgets on page 3
        of the configuration window.

        You can't move windows that are of full width or height.

        Selecting the @{"Reject This Screen" link "menus" 0} menu should also move Aavd to
        another screen.
@endnode

@node "future" "What will (may) happend in the future"

    @{b}Future@{ub}

        I havn't decided what to do if the user doubleclick the
        right button, any ideas??

        And maybe I will make a MUI version of AAVD later on, some
        time...

        Find out why you can't close CON: windows.

        Improve the way @{"JUMPSCROLL" link "use" 0} works.

        Add some more keyboard commands.

        Maybe an Arexxport??
@endnode

@node "history" "How it all used to be"

    @{b}History@{ub}

        @{b}1.5@{ub} 1995-04-30

            Added the @{"NOTEXT" link "use" 0} switch and the @{"FONTNAME" link "use" 0} and @{"FONTSIZE" link "use" 0}
            keywords. Aavd will now print the windowtitle in each
            box, using the font specified by @{"FONTNAME" link "use" 0} and with the
            size @{"FONTSIZE" link "use" 0}. This printing can be disabled by using
            the NOTEXT switch. Thanks to @{i}David Balazic@{ui} for this idea.

            Added a small feature to the @{"FOLLOW" link "use" 0} option. When the screen
            is scrolled more then 1/15th of the width or height, then the
            Aavd window is also moved up to the front. Thanks to @{i}David
            Balazic@{ui} for the idea.

            Added the @{"JUMPSCROLL" link "use" 0} switch. I think this is what
            @{i}Stephen Champion@{ui} wanted me to include...

            Added prefs-like menus to the configuration window.

            Added the @{"Reject This Screen" link "menus" 0} menuitem.

            Removed all (I think) enforcer hits (guess who just bought a
            50MHz 68030 :-).

            Added some new @{"keyboard-comands" link "keyboard" 0}.

            Removed a couple of minor bugs.

            Tiny improvements to the graphics.


        @{b}1.4@{ub} 1995-03-01

            Removed a bug that frooze the system when the @{"FOLLOW" link "use" 0} switch
            was used and you tried to move a window in such a way that
            the screen was scrolled.

            Added the @{"maximize" link "keyboard" 0} and @{"minimize" link "keyboard" 0} keyboard commands.

            Added @{"cursor key" link "keyboard" 0} support.

            Added the Activation hotkey.

            Now you're able to select what colors to use, and because of
            this the NOFANCY switch is no longer needed and therefore
            removed.

            Added some more menuitems, @{b}Use Current@{ub}, @{b}Save Current@{ub},
            @{b}Prefs@{ub} and @{b}About@{ub}.

            The snapshots are now saved. Thanks to @{i}Thomas Pazourek@{ui} for
            this idea.

            Removed the possibility to choose how to disable AAVD.
            Instead AAVD is now truley disabled.

            Rewrote the GUI once more...

            Fixed some minor bugs.

        @{b}1.3@{ub} 1995-02-01

            Made the patches safer. Now you will be asked how you
            want to quit if some of the functions AAVD has pacthed
            has been patched again after AAVD was started. Either you
            can quit as normal, or wait until the patch has been
            removed.
            You will also be warned if AAVD suspects that a program is
            executing code in AAVD's patches.

            Rewrote the GUI. Now it isn't fontsensitive anymore :-(

            Added support for tool types, that is, AAVD can now be
            started from WB. Thanks to @{i}Thomas Egeter@{ui} for this idea.

            Added @{"menus" link "menus" 0}. These are activated when you press the right
            mousebutton on the border or outside the window.

            Added the switch 'No title bar' (@{"NOTITLEBAR" link "use" 0} from shell).
            Thanks to @{i}Thomas Egeter@{ui} (again) for the idea.

            Fixed the '@{"Safe" link "use" 0}' switch.

            Changed the way of how "resize" works. Now the bottomright
            corner of the window will be on the mouse pointer.

            AAVD no longer draws the screen box outsize the screen.
            Thanks to @{i}Nicolas Dade@{ui} for reporting this bug.

            AAVD now locks all the layers on the screen before drawing
            the screenbox. This was suggested to my by @{i}Nicolas Dade@{ui}.

            The Screen Box is now draw in recessed 3d, unless the NOFANCY
            switch is used.

            Added the @{"DEVIDE" link "use" 0} switch.

            Added keyboard support, and the @{"Zoom" link "keyboard" 0} and @{"Kill" link "keyboard" 0} keys.

            Removed the bug when a box was left in the AAVD window if
            AAVD was inactive when the window manipulation was started.

            Now AAVD can be disabled from the Exchange tool.


        @{b}1.2b@{ub} 1994-11-12

            Minor bug fixed. Forgot to remove the text 'PRE-RELEASE' from
            the window's title bar.

        @{b}1.2@{ub} 1994-11-07

            Turned AAVD into a commoditiy. Now you can snapshot up
            to 4 positions and recall these positions later. Thanks to
            @{i}Kimmo Veijalainen@{ui} for this idea.

            AAVD no longer freezes the system when it failes to open
            the window. Thanks to @{i}Janne Saarme@{ui} for reporting this bug.

            Removed some other serious and not so serious bugs.


        @{b}1.1@{ub} 1994-10-09

            Fixed small bug when using the NOFANCY option. The color of
            the active window is now white, and not, as before, grey.

            Slightly modified the patch routines. Now AAVD will never
            redraw the window if an action fails, for example, someone
            tried to open a window, but failed for some reson.


        @{b}V1.0@{ub} 1994-06-26

            First version released.
@endnode

@node "bugreport" "Reporting Bugs"

    @{b}Bug Reports.@{ub}

        There are some things that I wish you to think of if you should
        encounter a bug, and feel that you would like to share it with
        me.

        First of all, it always nice to know which version of Aavd you
        are using. I really hate searching for bugs that have already
        been fixed :-)

        Second, try to describe exactly how you managed to get the bug
        A simple statement saying "It doesn't work." won't help me much.

        Check the @{"Known Bugs" link "bugs" 0} section. If the bug already is known, then
        there's really no point in reminding me. (But you could still
        send me a letter :-)

        It you are running some other "strange" utils, then check if Aavd
        will work better if you don't run them. It might happen that
        Aavd doesn't work together with another program, although this
        should be very rare.

        The hardware you're using could also be of intrest. Especially
        your os version.

        Feel free to comment the language in this doc :-)
@endnode

